The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal
 Tuesday, February 10, 2004 				 Schoolgirl saved from circus artiste 
 OUR CORRESPONDENT																								Howrah, Feb. 9: A mime artiste in circus, Aamir Khan, was arrested today and charged with being the kingpin of a girl-running racket.																								Khan and four of his associates were picked up from Pandua in Hooghly, about 60 km from Calcutta, and a girl of 15 was rescued. They were accused of kidnapping Shampa Bhakta, a Class IX student of a Howrah school. Shampas parents had lodged a missing diary with police in Jagachha when she failed to return home after school on January 27. 																								Those arrested confessed during interrogation that they were involved in the girl-running racket, said an official of Jagachha police station. Aamir had promised Shampa that he would marry her. However, his real plan was to sell her to a brothel, said superintendent of police Mihir Bhattacharya.																								The police rescued another girl, Tumpa Pal, from a brothel at Watgunge in Calcutta. Tumpa, a Class VIII student in Shampas school, had also gone missing on January 27.
